[The slow but continuous increase in yellow fever cases, including in the major metropolitan municipalities, is of concern. The report above provides a good update on the current YF situation in Brazil. There is no indication that the outbreak has ended. Although there still have been no reports of cases from the urban, _Aedes aegypti_, cycle of transmission, the risk remains that spillover from the sylvan (forest) cycle could occur. _Aedes aegypti_ vector mosquitoes are present in the area and responsible for the transmission of dengue, Zika, and chikungunya viruses. It is important to note from the case numbers above that cases of YF in humans and monkeys are occurring in areas outside of the 3 states where the main outbreak is occurring. There is risk of new human cases and outbreaks in other areas, so that surveillance in a broad area of Brazil is important. Expansion of the area for vaccination to ultimately include the entire country is prudent but ambitious. No comment is made above about the availability of vaccine for the 77.5 million people to be covered, nor if a fractionated or full dose of the vaccine will be administered. - Mod.TY

Maps of Brazil can be accessed at http://s13.postimg.org/jumnalk87/map_of_Brazil.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5747516,6.]
